        <h2>Computer Networking and Cloud Computing</h2>
        <p>Dr. Lavian offers networking expert consulting services involving computer networking systems, cloud computing infrastructure, network architecture design, and enterprise networking technologies. With extensive experience in both academic research and industry practice, Dr. Lavian provides expert analysis on complex networking disputes, patent litigation, and technology assessments.</p>

        <h3>Networking Expert</h3>
        <p>The following are Dr. Tal Lavian's areas of expertise in Networking:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Enterprise Network Architecture, Campus Networks, Data Center Networks, and Branch Office Networks</li>
          <li>Cloud Computing Platforms, IaaS, PaaS, SaaS, and Hybrid Cloud Architectures</li>
          <li>Software-Defined Networking (SDN), Network Function Virtualization (NFV), and Network Automation</li>
          <li>TCP/IP Protocol Suite, OSI Model, and Network Protocol Analysis</li>
          <li>Network Virtualization, VLAN, VxLAN, and Overlay Networks</li>
          <li>Content Delivery Networks (CDN), Load Balancing, and Traffic Management</li>
          <li>Network Performance Optimization, QoS, and Traffic Engineering</li>
          <li>Distributed Systems, Microservices Architecture, and Service Mesh</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Cloud Computing Technologies</h3>
        <p>Cloud computing has transformed how organizations deploy and manage their IT infrastructure. Cloud platforms provide on-demand access to computing resources, storage, and networking services. These platforms enable businesses to scale their operations dynamically while reducing capital expenditure on physical infrastructure.</p>

        <p>Key cloud computing models include Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), which provides virtualized computing resources; Platform as a Service (PaaS), which offers development and deployment environments; and Software as a Service (SaaS), which delivers applications over the Internet. Hybrid cloud architectures combine on-premises infrastructure with public cloud services, providing flexibility and control.</p>

        <h3>Enterprise Network Systems</h3>
        <p>Modern enterprise networks are complex systems that integrate wired and wireless connectivity, security infrastructure, and management tools. These networks must support diverse workloads including voice, video, data, and IoT traffic. Network architects design these systems to provide high availability, scalability, and security.</p>

        <p>Enterprise networking encompasses campus networks with hierarchical switch architectures, data center networks with spine-leaf topologies, wide area networks connecting geographically distributed sites, and branch office networks providing remote connectivity. Each component requires careful design to ensure optimal performance and reliability.</p>

        <h3>Software-Defined Networking</h3>
        <p>Software-Defined Networking (SDN) separates the network control plane from the data plane, enabling centralized management and programmability of network infrastructure. SDN controllers provide a global view of the network and can dynamically adjust routing, security policies, and quality of service parameters.</p>

        <p>Network Function Virtualization (NFV) complements SDN by virtualizing network services that traditionally ran on dedicated hardware. Functions such as firewalls, load balancers, and WAN optimizers can be deployed as software on standard servers, reducing costs and increasing deployment flexibility.</p>

        <h3>Network Architecture and Design</h3>
        <p>Network architecture involves the design and planning of communication networks to meet business requirements. This includes selecting appropriate protocols, topologies, and technologies to build reliable, scalable, and secure network infrastructure. Proper network design considers current requirements and future growth, ensuring the network can adapt to changing business needs.</p>

